sion suggests suitability for immunotherapy.\n\n\n## Clinical Implications\n- **Treatment relevance:** The KRAS G12C mutation and high PD-L1 expression identify specific therapeutic targets.  Treatment options should include consideration of targeted therapy with a KRAS G12C inhibitor (e.g., sotorasib, adagrasib) and/or immunotherapy with a PD-1/PD-L1 inhibitor (e.g., pembrolizumab, atezolizumab).  The optimal treatment strategy will depend on the patient's overall health, performance status, and the extent of disease as determined by further staging.\n- **Prognostic factors:** While the high PD-L1 expression is a positive prognostic indicator for immunotherapy, the presence of the KRAS mutation and evidence of lymph node involvement suggest an advanced stage, which could negatively impact prognosis.  A comprehensive staging workup is crucial for accurate prognostication.\n- **Additional testing needs:**\n    -  Further histological subtyping of the adenocarcinoma is recommended for a more precise classification and potential refinement of treatment strategies.\n    -  Additional immunohistochemical stains may be considered depending on the final histologic subtype.\n    -  Mutational analysis for other genes (e.g., HER2, MET) should be considered, although less likely to be relevant given the KRAS G12C mutation.\n    -  Tumor mutational burden (TMB) assessment might be useful to further guide immunotherapy decisions.",
