 option.\n\n\n## Clinical Implications\n- **Treatment relevance:** The KRAS G12C mutation and high PD-L1 expression provide several potential therapeutic avenues. Targeted therapy with a KRAS G12C inhibitor is a strong consideration, along with immunotherapy with a PD-1/PD-L1 inhibitor. A multidisciplinary team meeting should be held to discuss the optimal treatment strategy, taking into account the patient\u2019s overall health, performance status, and comorbidities.\n- **Prognostic factors:** The KRAS G12C mutation is associated with a more aggressive disease course compared to KRAS wild-type lung adenocarcinomas. The high PD-L1 expression may improve prognosis with immunotherapy. The patient's performance status will significantly influence treatment choices and overall prognosis.  Further staging is crucial to accurately assess prognosis.\n- **Additional testing needs:**  Further sampling is recommended to better assess the tumor grade and stage.  This could include surgical resection with lymph node dissection for definitive staging and further analysis, or additional biopsies guided by imaging to determine the extent of disease.  Testing for other relevant biomarkers (e.g., microsatellite instability, tumor mutational burden) may be considered to further refine treatment options.  A comprehensive evaluation of the patient's performance status is also essential.",
