argets:** The KRAS G12C mutation is a targetable mutation.  The high PD-L1 expression suggests potential benefit from immunotherapy.\n\n\n## Clinical Implications\n- **Treatment relevance:**  The presence of a KRAS G12C mutation and high PD-L1 expression significantly influences therapeutic options.  Sotorasib or adagrasib (KRAS G12C inhibitors) are potential treatment options.  Furthermore, immunotherapy with a PD-1/PD-L1 inhibitor may be considered, either as monotherapy or in combination with other agents.  The precise treatment approach will be determined by the MDT based on the patient's overall clinical status, performance status, and comorbidities.\n- **Prognostic factors:**  The moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma, the presence of N2 nodal involvement (based on imaging), and the KRAS mutation are factors that influence the patient's prognosis.  A more precise prognostic assessment will be possible after complete staging and treatment response evaluation.\n- **Additional testing needs:**  While the current molecular panel is comprehensive for initial therapeutic decision-making, additional testing may be warranted.  This includes comprehensive genomic profiling (CGP) to identify potential additional targetable mutations or genomic alterations that could guide therapy.  Further testing of resected tissue (if surgery is performed) will be invaluable for refining grade and assessing other prognostic features like lymphovascular and perineural invasion.  Mutation testing on lymph node samples, if available, would help in understanding the clonal relationship between the primary tumor and the metastasis.",
