on detected.  EGFR, ALK, and ROS1 were wild-type.\n   - **Biomarker levels:** PD-L1 expression: 80%.  This indicates high expression and suggests potential benefit from PD-1/PD-L1 inhibitors.\n   - **Therapeutic targets:** The KRAS G12C mutation is a therapeutic target for specific tyrosine kinase inhibitors (e.g., sotorasib, adagrasib). The high PD-L1 expression suggests potential benefit from immunotherapy (e.g., pembrolizumab, atezolizumab).\n\n\n## Clinical Implications\n- **Treatment relevance:** The KRAS G12C mutation and high PD-L1 expression significantly influence treatment decisions.  Targeted therapy with a KRAS G12C inhibitor and/or immunotherapy are viable options.  The presence of comorbidities (diabetes and hypertension) needs to be considered when choosing the treatment regimen.\n- **Prognostic factors:**  The stage of the disease (Stage IIIA, based on imaging) is a crucial prognostic factor.  The high PD-L1 expression is a positive prognostic indicator, but the presence of the KRAS mutation might somewhat mitigate that.  The patient's age and performance status will also be important factors in determining the prognosis and treatment plan.\n- **Additional testing needs:**  Further evaluation is needed to confirm the absence of lymphovascular invasion.  Comprehensive lymph node assessment (e.g., via EBUS-TBNA) is crucial for accurate staging and treatment planning.  Additional tissue samples from involved lymph nodes would help to confirm the presence of metastatic disease.  Further testing for other potentially targetable mutations (e.g., comprehensive genomic profiling or next-generation sequencing) could identify additional treatment options.  A detailed assessment of the patient's performance status is also necessary.",
